    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1524059800" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1524059800" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31667052-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589658539p2/31667052.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1524059800?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/31667052-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781411429932" href="/book/show/8922828-the-praise-of-folly">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1524059800" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9696637122520172438">Abandoning Praise of Folly at about 1/3 through. I didn’t understand it - there were a lot of references to Greek philosophers, etc. that were way over my head. I also was very disappointed in the lack of satire/humor. Maybe it was in there but I just didn’t get it? I’m disappointed in myself because this book is only 115 pages, but it just wasn’t for me. <br/><br/>I might try to pick this up again at some point, but life is too short for books that don’t make any sense to me.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

